        Contribute code via the <span class="underline hover:text-orange-400">Github repository</span>.
      </a>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2 class="mb-2 mt-8 uppercase font-bold tracking-wider text-gray-400">
    Where to Find Good Data
  </h2>
  <p>I am checking the data on a daily basis for Nashville <a class="underline hover:text-orange-400" href="https://www.asafenashville.org">on a website</a> that the City of Nashville set up to manage their coronavirus response in Nashville. If you can't find a reliable source from your state or local government, then <a class="underline hover:text-orange-400" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html">The NY Times county-by-county table</a> is a good source. They are not tracking these counties over time and sharing that data publicly, so that's where you step in. The key thing is to make sure to cite the source for your data and are transparent with date &amp; time you updated it.</p>
